The President of the United States convened a meeting with his public health and national security teams to discuss measures to mitigate the risk of additional domestic Ebola cases. The President emphasized that these measures should be guided by medical science and not discourage healthcare workers from serving. The participants in the meeting included the Vice President, Secretary of State, Secretary of Defense, Attorney General, Secretary of Health and Human Services, Secretary of Homeland Security, Chief of Staff, Director of the Office of Management and Budget, U.S. Permanent Representative to the United Nations, Assistant to the President for Intergovernmental Affairs and Public Engagement, National Security Advisor, Assistant to the President for Homeland Security and Counterterrorism, Counsel to the President, Director of the Office of Science and Technology, Ebola Response Coordinator, Director of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, Director of the Office of Legislative Affairs, Director of Communications, Assistant Secretary for International Markets and Development, Director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Disease, Assistant Administrator, Bureau for Democracy, Conflict, and Humanitarian Assistance, Chief of Staff of the National Security Council, Deputy Counsel to the President, Deputy Assistant to the President for Homeland Security, Deputy National Security Advisor to the Vice President, and Senior Director for Development and Democracy, National Security Council.